                           Muḥammad Zamān Shīrāzī</persName></handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <summary>Three illuminated headpieces:</summary>
                     <decoNote type="headpiece">Folio <locus from="1b" to="1b">1b</locus> bears a
                        scalloped domed headpiece with gilt palmette foliate scrollwork on an
                        ultramarine ground and an uninscribed central cartouche, and four vertical
                        radiating lines.<lb/>
                        <!--  <dimensions type="headpiece" unit="mm">
                           <height>100</height>
                           <width>55</width>
                        </dimensions> FINISH--></decoNote>
                     <decoNote type="marginal"><label>Ruling:</label> Folios <locus from="1b"
                           to="2a>">1b and 2a</locus> ruled in <material>gold</material> outlined
                        with thin black lines, and surrounded by another single line. The margins of
                        folios <locus from="2b">2b</locus> onwards ruled with single lines of
                        ultramarine blue.</decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <lb/><label>Inscriptions:</label> The <locus from="ia" to="ia">first right
                        flyleaf a side</locus> numbered <q xml:lang="en">D. F. 147</q> and priced <q
                        xml:lang="en">£4.4</q> in pencil at bottom, both pertaining to former owner
                        <persName type="standard" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/66617580/"
                        key="person_66617580" role="fmo ins" change="#role-assignment">Duncan
                        Forbes</persName>' catalogue.<lb/> Folio <locus from="1a" to="1b">1a</locus>
                     signed by former owner <persName type="standard" role="fmo ato seal"
                        key="person_f6703">Edward Galley</persName>.<lb/>
                     <label>Bookplates and labels:</label> Folio <locus from="229b" to="229b"
                        >229b</locus> bears an early Bibliotheca Lindesiana label:<lb/>
                     <q xml:lang="en">Persian MSS No. <hi rend="strikethrough">69</hi></q>, with the
                     number crossed out and <q xml:lang="en">853</q> written aside.<lb/> The <locus
                        from="Inner_back_cover" to="Inner_back_cover">left pastedown</locus> bears
                        <q xml:lang="en">Bibliotheca Lindesiana</q> bookplate with pencilled
                     shelfmark the <q xml:lang="en">F/6</q> and </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1775" notAfter="1838">
                        <p>Probably bound in <placeName
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000231" key="place_7000231"
                              >Greater Iran</placeName>.</p>
                        <p>Resewn at two stations, unsupported. Edges trimmed, stained brown, and
                           chevron endbands of yellow and green threads twined at <locus from="Head"
                              to="Head">head</locus> and <locus from="Tail" to="Tail">tail</locus>.
                           Covered in two pieces of shagreen <material>leather</material> over
                              <material>pastebaords</material>, which overlap, tight-backed, on the
                              <locus from="Spine" to="Spine">spine</locus>, with defined joints, and
                           a fore-edge and enevelope flap (Type II binding per Déroche). Internal
                           doublures of reddish-brown goatskin <material>leather</material>.</p>
                        <decoNote type="binding">Boards bear recessed gold-blocked red goatskin
                              <material>leather</material> onlays for the central scallopped
                           mandorlas that feature a pair of ducks, detached pendatns with lotus
                           blossoms, the lattwer also appears on the flap. Board margines ruled with
                           dsingle lines with flourishes that criss-cross the contral decoration,
                           and surround it, along with thick-and-thin lines along the board edges.
                              <locus from="Spine" to="Spine">Spine</locus> bears a printed paper
                           label with the title in Persian.</decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>235</height>
                              <width>138</width>
                              <depth>35</depth>
                           </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>Handle binding with caution. In fair but stable condition.
                        </condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
                     <summary>Seven black intaglio-carved seal impressions on folios <locus
                           from="1a" to="1b">1a to 1b</locus>:</summary>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="rectangle">
                        <p><label>1:</label> Folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus>, top-centre,
                           bears a small rectangular impression in three stacked naskh lines, read
                           from bottom up, single-ruled, which invokes the twelfth Imām Muḥammad
                           Mahdī, hence possibly a namesake seal for a man of that name:<lb/>
                           <q xml:lang="ar">یا امام محمد مهدی</q><lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>9</height>
                              <width>10</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="rectangle">
                        <p><label>2:</label> Folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> bears a
                           single impression of <persName role="seal ato ins" key="person_f6703"
                              >Edward Galley</persName>'s small oval seal, intaglio carved in one
                           nasta‘līq script line, double-ruled:<lb/>
                           <q>ادورد گلی</q>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>11</height>
                              <width>13</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="oval">
                        <p><label>3:</label> Folio Folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> bears
                           one faint oval seal impression of a <hi rend="italic">basmala</hi> in
                           three stacked lines of thuluth script against a floral scrollwork ground,
                           read from bottom up, double-ruled, bears a date of <date
                              calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1693" to="1693">1105 AH (1693–1694
                              CE)</date>:<lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>14</height>
                              <width>23</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="rectangle">
                        <p><label>5:</label> Folio <locus from="1b" to="1b">1b</locus> also bear two
                           small rectangular impressions in two stacked thuluth lines read from
                           bottom up, single-ruled, which features Qur'ān Sūrah Yā-Sīn, 36:58:<lb/>
                           , may also be a namesake seal for a man named ‘Abd al-Raḥīm:<lb/>
                           <q xml:lang="ar">سَلامٌ قَوْلًا مِنْ رَبٍّ رَحِيمٍ</q><lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>13</height>
                              <width>15</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="rectangle">
                        <p><label>6:</label> Folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> also bears
                           another slightly smaller rectangular impression in three stacked thuluth
                           lines read from the middle upwards then bottom, double-ruled, which also
                           features Qur'ān Sūrah Yā-Sīn, 36:58:<lb/> , may also be a namesake seal
                           for a man named ‘Abd al-Raḥīm:<lb/>
                           <q xml:lang="ar">سَلامٌ قَوْلًا مِنْ رَبٍّ رَحِيمٍ</q><lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>11</height>
                              <width>14</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="rectangle">
                        <p><label>6:</label> Folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> bears another
                           small rectangular impression in two stacked nasta‘līq lines read from top
                           down, double-ruled, with a namesake seal for someone named <persName
                              role="seal">Muḥammad ‘Azīz</persName> against a floral scrollwork ground:<lb/>
                           <q xml:lang="ar">محمد عزیز مهر کرده مرا</q><lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>8</height>
                              <width>10</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="rectangle">
                        <p><label>6:</label> Folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> bears another
                           very small partial rectangular impression in two stacked nasta‘līq lines
                           read from top down, double-ruled, with an excerpt from Qur]ān Surah
                           Ghāfir (The Forgiver, 40:44) with the name of one <persName role="seal"
                              >‘Abd al-Raḥīm</persName> against a floral scrollwork ground:<lb/>
                           <q xml:lang="ar">أُفَوِّضُ أَمْرِي إِلَى اللَّهِ عبد الرحيم</q><lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>8</height>
                              <width>10</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="rectangle">
                        <p><label>8:</label> Folios <locus from="1b" to="1b">1b</locus>, top above
                           the headpiece, and <locus from="229a" to="229a">229a</locus>, bottom by
                           the colophon, bear very small oval impressions in one nasta‘līq with the
                           name <persName role="seal">‘Azīz</persName> against a floral scrollwork
                           ground, dated <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" notBefore="1735"
                              notAfter="1736">1148 AH (1735–1736 CE)</date>:<lb/>
                           <q xml:lang="ar"> عزیز ۱۱۴۸</q><lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>7.5</height>
                              <width>11</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                  </sealDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>Completed by <persName role="scr">Khvājah Muḥammad Zamān
                        Shīrāzī</persName> in the <origPlace cert="high" type="empire"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/6005089" key="place_6005089">Safavid
                        Empire</origPlace>. possibly at <origPlace cert="medium"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7002148" key="place_7002148"
                        >Shiraz</origPlace>
                     <origDate calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1667-09-20">1 Rabī‘ II 1078 AH (20
                        Sept. 1667 CE)</origDate>.</origin>
                  <provenance><p>Subsequently owned or inspected by at least four individuals, 3 of
                        whom left namesake seal impressions on folios <locus from="1a" to="1b">1a
                           and 1b</locus> dated <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1693" to="1693"
                           >1105 AH (1693–94 AH)</date> and another of <persName role="seal">Sayyid
                           Abū al-Fatḥ Mustaqīm</persName>, dated <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari"
                           from="1761" to="1762">1175 AH (1761–62 AH)</date>, as well as ownership
                        notes by <persName role="ato ins fmo">Ḥājjī Muhammad Ṣarrāf
                           Iṣfahānī</persName> and his son <persName role="ato fmo ins">Muḥammad
                           Ṭālib</persName> on folios <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> and the
                        latter again on <locus from="402b" to="402b">402b</locus>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance/>
                  <provenance><p>Later acquired by <persName type="standard" role="fmo ato seal"
                           key="person_f6703">Edward Galley (ca. 1750–1804)</persName>, <orgName
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/239176400">East India Company</orgName>
                        Resident at <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7018005"
                           key="place_7018005">Bushire (Bushehr)</placeName> between <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" from="1780" to="1787">1780 to 1787</date>, where he
                        probably obtained this volume. Ultimately Lieutentant-Governor of <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001592" key="place_7001592"
                           >Surat</placeName> where he passed away, after his death, Galley's family
                        sold a portion of his library in Surat including volumes obtained by David
                        Price (see Robinson, p. 209). However, they evidently returned to Britain
                        and subsequently sold the remainder through the <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781">London</placeName> firm of
                           <persName role="auc" key="person_10201461">Samuel Leigh
                           Sotheby</persName> on <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1837-06-30">30
                           June 1837</date>, lot 214.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Probably acquired at Galley's sale by <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781">London</placeName>
                        bookseller <persName role="bsl" cert="high"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/12688740" key="person_12688740">Henry George
                           Bohn (1796–1884)</persName>, who then offered it for sale in his <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1841">1841</date> catalogue, no. 13638,
                        described in the present binding for 2£ 12<hi rend="italic">s</hi> 6<hi
                           rend="italic">d</hi>. </p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Probably purchased from Bohn by orientalist <persName type="standard"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/66617580/" key="person_66617580" role="fmo"
                           change="#role-assignment">Duncan Forbes (1798–1868)</persName>.
                        Ultimately appointed <orgName>King's College</orgName> Professor of Oriental
                        Languages, Forbes described this volume in his <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                           when="1866">1866</date> catalogue, valued at £6 16<hi rend="italic"
                           >s</hi> and 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>
                        <!-- (also inscribed on the <locus
                           from="Inner_front_cover" to="Inner_front_cover">right pastedown</locus>) -->,
                        before he sold his manuscript collection to his publisher <orgName
                           role="bsl" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/152259747" key="person_152259747"
                              ><persName key="person_45159035185601380002" role="bsl"
                              change="#prov-markup">W. H. Allen </persName>&amp; Co.</orgName> in
                        exchange for an annuity.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Subsequently sold by <orgName role="bsl"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/152259747" key="person_152259747"><persName
                              key="person_45159035185601380002" role="bsl" change="#prov-markup">W.
